<li>[[Smart Contracts]]</li>
<li>Protocols
<ul>
<li>[[IPFS]] or InterPlanetary File System
<ul>
<li>This looks akin to other P2P protocols of the past like Bit Torrent</li>
<li>The idea is for all of us to become not only consumers of the Internet but also its hosts—once again one might say since web1 was decentralized, web2 is very centralized (Google, Facebook, etc), and web3, we hope, is going to be decentralized once again.</li>
<li>The objective of this protocol is to bring us all a step closer to a fully decentralized and more resilient internet that can be robust against attacks (if a DDoS attack reaches Wikipedia, it goes down and nobody can access it, using IPFS this is prevented) and censorhip (governments now can just block a few routes and servers, using IPFS it will be way more difficult for them to do so)</li>
<li>The most interesting part of the protocol is the [[Content addressing]]. It totally changes the game because now things are addressable by a hash of their content and not their location. This makes sense if anybody can host pieces of the data</li>
<li>refs:
<ul>
<li>https://github.com/ipfs/awesome-ipfs</li>
<li>https://docs.ipfs.io/concepts/usage-ideas-examples/</li>
</ul></li>
</ul></li>
</ul></li>
